   ENERGY
                                                                                                       

       2nd QTR. 1990           2ND QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

        4,531,106               4,053,662           + 12
                                                                                                       

   In the oil field sector, a pickup of more than 20% in U.S.
drilling activity along with steady overseas activity boosted
re sults. The giant equipment and service companies reaped
the benefits of several years of cost-cutting and industry
consolidation. A number of companies also said they were able
to make price increases that stuck. And drilling companies
narrowed their losses as restructuring is paying off. This
sector could show steady improvement if expected increases in
drilling activity materialize.
   With prices and volume low for the quarter, natural-gas
pipeline companies felt the pinch. Customers in the Northeast
switched to other fuels, while markets in the Midwest
continue to be overrun with competitors. Those and other
factors combined to hammer Panhandle Eastern, which slashed
its dividend 60% and expects more belt-tightening because of
environmental cleanup costs and adverse regulatory rulings.
That company has tabled a number of expansion projects and
could see a further drop in volume when certain rates to the
Northeast go up in December. Meanwhile, Burlington Resource's
pipeline unit saw a 4% increase in operating profit.
   Coal companies posted higher earnings for the quarter
largely from stronger prices and volume. Another reason for
the improvement was that last year's results were hurt by
wildcat strikes staged in support of the United Mine Workers
union against Pittston.
                                                                                                       

