   INDUSTRIAL
                                                                                                       

       2ND QTR. 1990           2ND QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

        3,625,334               3,814,644           -  5
                                                                                                       

   Slow industrial freight shipments pared rail earnings at
Consolidated Rail, Norfolk Southern and Santa Fe Pacific. But
Burlington Northern benefited from strong coal shipments, and
CSX reported improved results at its rail, barge and
container shipping units. Excluding gains of $62 million from
sale of subsidiaries in the 1989 quarter, CSX's earnings from
continuing operations rose 20%.
   Trucking-company earnings were hurt by overcapacity and
higher fuel and labor costs. Consolidated Freightways said
losses at its Emery air-freight unit more than offset
earnings improvement at its truck units. A 3% rate increase
implemented in June is expected to boost third-quarter
results for carriers that handle less than full-truckload
shipments.
   The slump in second-quarter net at American President, an
ocean, rail and truck transporter, reflected a decline in
international shipment volumes, rate pressures and increased
equipment costs.
   The air-freight industry performed about as expected, with
Airborne Freight continuing its torrid growth and Federal
Express still having problems overseas. Airborne, known as
the industry's lowest-cost producer, is still benefiting from
problems at Consolidated Freightways' Emory unit, and may
also be eating into Federal Express's U.S. business. Federal
Express continues to post international losses of millions of
dollars a month, and is facing lower Asian demand and slower
U.S. volume growth as well. Airborne is expected to continue
its heady growth, while there's no end in sight for Federal's
woes.
   In transportation equipment, the downturn in the market
for big trucks continued to squeeze profits, and there's no
consensus on when a rebound might start. Navistar sees an 18%
decline in industry shipments of heavy trucks and a 4%
decline in medium trucks for its fiscal year, which ends Oct.
31. Cummins Engine says third-quarter production of heavy
trucks is expected to fall 10% from a year earlier; it
expects a loss for the period. But Eaton, which makes truck
transmissions and axles, sees "indications" the heavy truck
market will improve by year end.
   Profit gains continued for heavy machinery, but a steep
decline at giant Caterpillar dragged down overall results.
Brazil's stiff anti-inflation and economic-reform plan was
partly behind the tumbling profit at Caterpillar. Troubles in
Brazil also curbed the profit gain at Clark Equipment. Sales
of Caterpillar's construction equipment slowed in the U.S.
and other industrialized nations. For the full year, the
company expects "substantially lower" profit than in 1989.
While farm-equipment sales for companies such as Deere are
likely to continue robust, there are signs of a slowdown for
other heavy machinery. Clark says "emerging softness in world
markets" could reduce its second-half earnings. Deere is "cau
tious" on the outlook for sales of its construction equipment
in North America.
                                                                                                       

