   CONSUMER, CYCLICAL
                                                                                                       

       2ND QTR. 1990           2ND QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

        5,937,840               8,619,109           - 31
                                                                                                       

   Housing starts fell again in the second quarter,
particularly in the northeastern U.S., reflecting weakening
demand and a liquidity crunch affecting small builders
brought on by the S&amp;L debacle. In California, where
homebuilding had remained relatively healthy, concern over
anticipated defense cuts has stalled consumer confidence and
started to weigh heavily on new construction. Standard
Pacific and Kaufman &amp; Broad said the weakening California
market contributed to earnings declines. Analysts predict a
continued drop in homebuilding through year end.
   Retailers are likely to report mixed results for the July
quarter. But some companies posting higher profits are
expected to show smaller increases than in recent quarters.
   Sears Roebuck, which operates on a calendar year, already
reported a 39% decline in net income; but sluggish sales and
higher expenses resulted in a 78% profit plunge at the
company's core U.S. retail business. Analysts expect J.C. Pen
ney to report sharply lower earnings, and Nordstrom and
Dayton Hudson are likely to post slightly lower net. U.S.
Shoe projects a profit decline because of falling sales at
its Lenscrafters stores. Earnings growth is likely to remain
robust at Wal-Mart, Dillard, Limited and Gap. K mart is
expected to show a small increase in profit.
   Hotel and casino companies faced continued overcapacity in
the lodging market, as well as new casino competition. Some
hotel operators, including Marriott, Motel 6 and La Quinta
Motor Inns, reported slight to moderate improvement in
operating results. Hilton Hotels experienced mixed results
from its hotels and a sharp drop in operating revenue at one
of its Las Vegas, Nev., casinos. Golden Nugget's large new
Las Vegas casino-resort produced a major improvement in
earnings, while Aztar's operating improvement was
overshadowed by a provision for a legal judgment against the
company. Circus Circus Enterprises' fiscal quarter ended
April 30 didn't include results from its big new casino in
Las Vegas.
   Some analysts worry that sluggishness in consumer spending
may rub off on travel and tourism in this quarter.
   The restaurant business generally remained soft. Price
discounting at fast-food sites was rampant, intensifying
competition and squeezing profit margins. McDonald's 10%
earnings gain trailed analysts' expectations. The quarter was
brighter for casual sit-down places, such as Shoney's.
   Casual sit-down restaurants have benefited from the
narrowing gap in non-promotional menu prices between
midpriced diners and fast-food outlets. For the third
quarter, with the same trends intact, Montgomery Securities
forecasts a 12% increase in McDonald's per-share earnings and
a 44% gain for Shoney's.
   Entertainment-industry earnings "are becoming weaker,"
said Harold Vogel, a first vice president at Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co. "The domestic box office is down from a year ago and the
cost of making and releasing films is up." Theme-park
attendance, he said, "has flattened out for the current
quarter." Lisbeth Barron, a vice president of research at
S.G. Warburg Securities, said Time Warner was hurt by
weakness in magazine earnings and flat performance in its
Home Box Office unit. "The record business has slowed
dramatically," she added. Paramount's year-earlier results
include $70.9 million in after-tax income from discontinued
operations.
   Demand for outboard engines continued to decline.
"Sluggish demand for boats continues. It's more of the same
for Outboard Marine and Brunswick," said Mr. Vogel.
   In the media sector, television networks stood out with
moderate to strong results. CBS was boosted largely by its
telecast of the National Basketball Association playoffs and
championship game, and by a drop in programming cost from a
year earlier. At Capital Cities/ABC, lukewarm results were
due to sluggish advertising sales at its television and radio
stations and to losses on the new baseball contract at its
80%-owned cable channel, ESPN.
   Ad demand continued its fall for most newspapers, and that
led to poor results for most newspaper-based media companies.
Gannett, the country's largest newspaper publisher, reported
its first quarterly drop in earnings in more than 22 years.
   Although fuel prices moderated somewhat,
weaker-than-expected domestic traffic and select fare wars
depressed airline earnings. Results at AMR's American
Airlines also were hurt by start-up costs for its new service
to Latin America. Midway Airlines' loss reflected continuing
expenses at its new Philadelphia hub. Delta was aided last
year by a strike at its chief competitor on the East Coast,
Eastern Airlines. UAL would have seen its profit fall if it
hadn't been for a one-time gain of $77.3 million from the
sale of aircraft.
   Analysts are predicting the third quarter will be even
more disappointing for the airlines than the second quarter
was because of slow traffic and fare discounting. "We were
looking to start to see improvement in the third quarter, but
that's now looking tough," one analyst said.
                                                                                                       

