   CONSUMER, NONCYCLICAL
                                                                                                       

       2ND QTR. 1990           2ND QTR. 1989       % CHG.
                                                                                                       

        6,343,350               5,849,557          +  8
                                                                                                       

   The food sector's strong showing reflected healthy sales
and lower commodities prices. More abundant soybean and corn
crops helped Archer-Daniels-Midland's results grow
substantially. General Mills benefited from continued good
volume gains of ready-to-eat cereals. Campbell Soup cited
better cost controls in North America and higher profit in
Argentina. Dean Foods, alone in reporting a decline in net
income, actually posted an operating earnings gain, but
year-earlier figures included proceeds from the sale of its
Baskin-Robbins business. Hershey Foods' latest results
include a $35 million gain from sale of a Swedish
confectionery unit. Prudential-Bache Securities food analyst
John McMillin expects many sector companies to report
low-double-digit profit gains for the current quarter.
   Food retailers continued to enjoy healthy to
better-than-expected overall gains, thanks to robust sales,
improved margins, better cost controls and lower interest
rates. Analysts cited the greater control that supermarket
companies are exercising in wholesale buying and continued
expansion of upscale specialty departments.
   Von's reversed the loss it sustained a year earlier after
absorbing the acquisi tion of Safeway's stores in Southern
California.
   From beer to soft drinks to bottling, the big beverage
companies uncorked profit increases. Strong business overseas
more than offset weak sales at home for Coca-Cola. Pepsi's
domestic soft-drink volume growth outpaced Coke's, and
Pepsi's earnings were bolstered by higher sales of snack and
restaurant foods. Coca-Cola Enterprises' net included several
extraordinary items, notably a $55.6 million pretax gain from
the sale of a business. Anheuser-Busch and Adolph Coors
reported higher beer shipments, reflecting strong sales of
new brands.
   Personal care companies reported solid earnings.
International sales remained strong, while continued low
materials costs and slight price increases boosted profits.
Neutrogena, a specialty soap and shampoo maker, was the clear
exception; earnings plunged because of increased competition,
swollen inventories and problems with new products.
   Profits continued strong for household product concerns,
and profit margins continued to expand, thanks in part to a
long truce in the consumer goods marketing wars. With
international sales healthy, profits got a boost from
favorable currency translations. More of the same is expected
for the current quarter.
   Once again, tobacco makers reported large gains, despite
the industry's troubled image. Strong sales overseas and
smaller-than-expected volume decreases in the U.S. are
expected to continue.
                                                                                                       

