   TECHNOLOGY
                                                                                                       

       2ND QTR. 1990           2ND QTR. 1989       % CHG.
                                                                                                       

        4,604,585               4,721,834          - 2
                                                                                                       

   Industry "fragmentation" is the watchword in
semiconductors, with Intel enjoying big profit from its
microprocessor monopoly while companies selling more standard
chips, such as Advanced Micro and National, see profit
margins eroded by price competition. Analysts expect Intel to
maintain a fat profit in the current quarter while a seasonal
summer slowdown brings continued sluggishness for other chip
makers and for equipment makers such as Applied Materials,
which still feel lingering effects of last year's chip slump.
Companies expect the profit picture to remain fragmented
until next year, when chip demand is expected to pick up
across the board. National had a $174 million special gain in
the 1989 quarter.
   Software makers continued to benefit from strong sales of
desktop computers and the growing appetite for more
sophisticated business software. Lotus Development posted the
biggest profit gain on the strength of broad acceptance of
its newest spreadsheet products. Microsoft's net income was
boosted by rapid growth in Europe and the initial reaction to
its new version of its Windows product. Novell and Oracle
Systems were aided by the continued shift to networked
computing, which puts a premium on the data base and
networking software sold by them.
   At American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, a costly credit-card
launch and sluggish equipment sales shaved long-distance
gains and cut profit. Motorola's profit increase was powered
mainly by higher semiconductor and cellular equipment sales.
Communications Satellite inched up after software problems in
its Video Entertainment unit offset gains in its
International and Systems businesses.
   Most aerospace companies' results reflected general
weakness in Pentagon contracting. The big loser was General
Dynamics, which took a stunning $500 million in write-offs to
reflect overruns on the Navy's A-12 attack plane program and
the Army's Sincgars radio project. McDonnell Douglas,
co-developer of the A-12, used a different accounting method
and sidestepped any charges. A year earlier, it posted $93
million in write-offs on its C-17 military cargo and KC-10
tanker programs. Northrop's year-before results included a
$150 million loss provision on a classified research
contract.
   The outlook is mixed, with commercial aircraft makers and
defense-electronics companies expected to outperform the
field. Peter Aseritis of First Boston says the picture will
become clearer only after the pending military budget is
complete.
   Many medical-equipment makers continued to benefit from
dominant positions in specialized and stable markets. In the
biotechnology field, Amgen remained one of the few concerns
that could cultivate a profit, as many companies remained in
the start-up phase.
   St. Jude Medical said the latest period's results
reflected continued penetration of its primary heart-valve
market. Stryker has achieved its growth rate by bringing out
such well-received products as hip implants and surgical
tools.
   In general, "there is a greater certainty of earnings
growth with health care relative to other industries," said
Leonard Yaffe, an analyst at Montgomery Securities. "Given
the demographics and pricing flexibility, companies can grow
at more predictable rates."
                                                                                                       

