<HL>
   Perini Is Suspending
   Payout as Cash Flow
   Fell in 2nd Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
08/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5B
</SO>
<CO>
   PNV
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- Perini Investment Properties Inc.
said it suspended its dividend and announced a decline in
second-quarter cash flow to three cents a share from 23 cents
in the year-ago period.
   The real-estate investment trust blamed the decline on a
drop in distributions from joint ventures, which it called
"largely a timing item," increased interest payments in the
quarter and a decline in cash flow from certain operating
properties.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said it expects these conditions to affect
operating cash flow for the remainder of the year. But it
said that certain planned transactions "could significantly
improve" results.
   In a statement, the company said it elected to suspend the
dividend in keeping with the board's policy of paying out 50%
to 60% of current cash flow. But the statement said the board
reaffirmed its belief that the net current per-share value of
the company's assets is "substantially in excess" of the
current share price.
