<HL>
   Duties Are Suggested
   For Certain Sweaters
   From South Korea
</HL>
<DATE>
08/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Commerce Department said anti-dumping
duties ranging from 1.7% to 3.17% should be assessed on
imports of synthetic-fiber sweaters from South Korea.
   Before the duties can be applied, however, the U.S.
International Trade Commission must decide whether the
imports, which totaled $476.1 million last year, have injured
the domestic industry. Affirmative rulings by both agencies
are required in anti-dumping cases.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The duties would offset the advantage of imports priced
below the cost of production or below the price charged in
South Korea's home market.
   The Commerce Department delayed until Aug. 20 its
determination on what anti-dumping duties should be imposed
on sweater imports from Taiwan. Earlier, the department found
that some Hong Kong sweater manufacturers also have violated
the U.S. Anti-Dumping Act.
   The ITC has scheduled a hearing for Thursday on sweater
imports from all three major Asian suppliers.
   The Commerce Department said the dumping margins on the
imports from South Korea averaged 3.17% on man-made fiber
sweaters -- including jackets, vests, cardigans and pullover
garments -- manufactured by Hanil Synthetic Fiber Industrial
Co. and smaller amounts for sweaters produced by other
companies. These included 1.2% for Chunji Industrial Co.,
1.11% for Shinwon Tongsan, 0.92% for Yurim Co., 0.73% for
Young Woo &amp; Co. and 1.3% for all other South Korean
producers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900806-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900806-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Nine High Priests
   Interpret U.S. Holy Writ
</HL>
<DATE>
08/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   Regarding your June 27 editorial "The Court's Angels": the
U.S. Constitution can hardly be ". . . transformed into Holy
Writ. . . ." It always has been Holy Writ. The English
refugees who first settled these shores came here in large
part because the medieval mind-set of Tudor England was being
replaced by James I's modernizing ideas, and those who
couldn't adapt emigrated.
   The essence of medieval polity was that all authority was
ultimately vested in "natural law," i.e. God's law, which was
interpreted for the people's use by the church. While the
drafters of our Constitution were far removed from medieval
times ecclesiastically, their political instincts were still
rooted in Tudor England, not Stuart, Orange or Hanoverian.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Compare Britain and the U.S. in terms of the locus of
"sovereignty." In the former, the law is whatever the House
of Commons says it is, and that House is by and large a fair
reflection of the "vox populi". "The people" are, through the
representational mechanism of the House of Commons, indeed
sovereign.
   In the U.S., by contrast, sovereignty is vested in a piece
of paper, the meaning of which, while reasonably clear when
written, is now available to the people only through the
interpretation of the Supreme Court. Our elected
representatives, both executive and legislative, are helpless
in the face of contrary "interpretations" by a majority of
our nine high priests.
   You and I may understand, for example, that so long as the
U.S. does not have an "official" church, the Constitution's
prohibition of the "establishment" of religion is being
complied with, and no further action or decision is
necessary. However, the simple words in the Constitution no
longer mean what they say; they mean whatever our unelected
lifetime-appointed neoclergy decides they mean.
   Therefore, unless there is a fundamental restructuring of
the American system of government, the Constitution will
remain, rather than be transformed into, "Holy Writ." I leave
it to you and your readers to figure out what can be done
about it.
   David B. Seidler
   Fair Lawn, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900806-0111
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900806-0111.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Coats Viyella Sells
   Some Assets to Clear
   Way for Tootal Bid
</HL>
<DATE>
08/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5B
</SO>
<CO>
   U.CVY U.TOT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Coats Viyella PLC, a U.K. textile maker, said it
satisfied regulatory conditions for a bid for Tootal Group
PLC, another U.K. textile group.
   Coats Viyella said it sold its U.K. thread business to
Amann &amp; Soehne G.m.b.H., a West German textile group, for an
undisclosed sum.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Monopolies and Mergers Commission said in October that
Coats could only take over Tootal if it disposed of all of
its U.K. interests in domestic sewing thread supply and its
shares in Gutermann Group.
   In December, the friendly #395 million ($732.6 million)
bid foundered following the breakdown of talks between the
two companies. Tootal said at the time that the offer failed
to reflect the company's strengths and prospects.
   Russell Walls, finance director of Coats Viyella, said the
company was now "free from any restrictions" to bid for
Tootal. He added that no negotiations were taking place
between the two companies.
   Coats Viyella sold its stake in the Gutermann Group to the
Gutermann family in May for an undisclosed sum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
