<HL>
   Newsprint Production
   By Mills in Canada
   Declined 3.4% in June
</HL>
<DATE>
08/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- Canadian production of newsprint in June
dropped 3.4% from a year earlier, as the industry operated at
95% of capacity.
   The Canadian Pulp and Paper Association, an industry
group, said Canadian mills produced 762,000 metric tons of
newsprint in June, compared with 789,000 a year earlier. A
metric ton is equal to about 2,204.62 pounds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the first six months, output fell 1.9% to 4,733,000
metric tons from 4,826,000 a year earlier.
   The June operating rate of 95% was down from 97% in May
and unchanged from a year earlier.
   June shipments fell less than 1% to 804,000 metric tons
from 809,000 a year earlier. Shipments to the U.S. fell, and
shipments to Canada and other markets rose. In the first
half, shipments rose less than 1% to 4,738,000 metric tons
from 4,705,000 a year earlier.
   The association said U.S. consumer stocks at the end of
June totaled 1,308,000 metric tons, a 41-day supply, up from
1,299,000 at the end of May, a 39-day supply, and up from
1,300,000, a 42-day supply, at the end of June 1989.
   Canadian mills' stocks at the end of June totaled 316,000
metric tons, compared with 358,000 at the end of May and
372,000 at the end of June 1989.
</TEXT>
